<body>
<div id="maintext">


<!-- ================================= -->
<h1 id=top> Metal Maps Gallery </h1>
<!-- ================================= -->

<p>
Ever wanted to make your python plots more metal? Fear not, now you can!
<i>metalmaps</i> delivers heavy metal and classic rock album art inspired 
matplotlib colormaps. For installation instructions and other details, please
visit the <a href="https://github.com/mladenivkovic/metalmaps">github repository</a>.
This page provides a gallery of all available colormaps below.
</p>


<p>
But first, credit where credit is due:

<ul>
  <li> 
    All of this was inspired by (and shamelessly copied from) Josh Borrow's 
    <a href="https://github.com/jborrow/swiftascmaps">swiftascmaps</a>
  </li>
  <li> 
    The "Kelvin-Helmholtz" data used in the plots below were generated using 
    <a href="https://github.com/mladenivkovic/mesh-hydro">mesh-hydro</a>.  
  </li>
  <li> 
    The "EAGLE" data used in the plots below were obtained from the 
    <a href="https://github.com/SWIFTSIM/SWIFT">swiftsim repository</a>.
  </li>
  <li> 
    The "NGC" data used in the plots below were originally obtained from 
    <a href="https://www.flickr.com/photos/geckzilla/52040747525/">flickr</a>,
    credits to <a href="https://www.flickr.com/people/geckzilla/">Judy Schmidt</a>.
    I modified the image later to normalize the pixel values to be able to demonstrate
    the colormaps as below.
  </li>
  <li>
    The album covers are linked over from <a href="https://musicbrainz.org/"> musicbrainz.org</a>.
  </li>
</ul>
</p>






